First of all, use `LocalDate` for handling dates. Whenever you deal with dates/times, you should strongly consider using `java.time` over `String`s. You can convert `String`s to `LocalDate`s using `LocalDate.parse`:

```java
DateTimeFormatter formatter = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(&quot;yyyy-MM-dd&quot;);
LocalDate startDate = LocalDate.parse(fromDate, formatter);
LocalDate endDate = LocalDate.parse(toDate, formatter);
```

Then, you can just add one day over and over until you reach the same date:
```java
for(LocalDate date = startDate; !endDate.isBefore(date); date = date.plusDays(1)){
    dates.add(date.format(formatter));
    //dates.add(date);//if you want to work with a List&lt;LocalDate&gt;
}
```

Summing up, you can use it in your method like this:

```java
public List&lt;String&gt; getDatesBetween(@NotEmpty String fromDate, @NotEmpty String toDate) throws Exception {
    List&lt;String&gt; dates = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    DateTimeFormatter formatter = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(&quot;yyyy-MM-dd&quot;);
    LocalDate startDate = LocalDate.parse(fromDate, formatter);
    LocalDate endDate =  LocalDate.parse(toDate, formatter);
    for(LocalDate date = startDate; !endDate.isBefore(date); date = date.plusDays(1)){   
      dates.add(date.format(formatter));
    }
    return dates;
}
```

As, [shmosel mentioned in the comments](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/75589148/java-get-list-date-between-2-dates/75589219?noredirect=1#comment133359099_75589219), `LocalDate` uses the [`ISO_LOCAL_DATE`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.base/java/time/format/DateTimeFormatter.html#ISO_LOCAL_DATE) by default so you don&#39;t have to provide a `DateTimeFormatter` in your case:

```java
public List&lt;String&gt; getDatesBetween(@NotEmpty String fromDate, @NotEmpty String toDate) throws Exception {
    List&lt;String&gt; dates = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    LocalDate startDate = LocalDate.parse(fromDate);
    LocalDate endDate =  LocalDate.parse(toDate);
    for(LocalDate date = startDate; !endDate.isBefore(date); date = date.plusDays(1)){
        dates.add(date.toString());
    }
    return dates;
}
```

## Java9+

You can use [`LocalDate::datesUntil`][1] which is introduced from Java9:

&gt; `public Stream&lt;LocalDate&gt; datesUntil​(LocalDate endExclusive)` &lt;br/&gt;
&gt; Returns a **sequential ordered stream of dates**. The returned stream starts from
&gt; this date (inclusive) and goes to endExclusive (exclusive) by an
&gt; incremental step of 1 day. &lt;br/&gt;This method is equivalent to
&gt; `datesUntil(endExclusive, Period.ofDays(1))`.


    public List&lt;String&gt; getDatesBetween(@NotEmpty String fromDate, @NotEmpty String toDate){
        LocalDate startDate = LocalDate.parse(fromDate);
        LocalDate endDate = LocalDate.parse(toDate);
        return startDate.datesUntil(endDate.plusDays(1))
                .map(LocalDate::toString)
                .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }

## Java8

I notice that you edit your question to ask for a solution using Java8, in this case, you can use:

    LocalDate startDate = LocalDate.parse(fromDate);
    LocalDate endDate = LocalDate.parse(toDate);
    return Stream.iterate(startDate, d -&gt; d.plusDays(1))
            .limit(ChronoUnit.DAYS.between(startDate, endDate.plusDays(1)))
            .map(LocalDate::toString)
            .collect(Collectors.toList());


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/docs/api/java/time/LocalDate.html#datesUntil-java.time.LocalDate-

